<font color="#FF0000">COOKIE'S POINT</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct 17 20:29:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cookie makes an interesting point.<br><br>
Southeast Asia has been an historical meatgrinder all by itself. Our presence was but a brief interlude in the saga of carnage going both back and forward in time.<br><br>
If we try to think of the events of the Vietnam War in the context of what we understand to be the cultural imperative of diminished regard for human life, then it could be argued that none of this truly has any significance. The &quot;killing fields&quot; of unrepentant butchery in Cambodia, and elsewhere, give the impression that these things are more of a way of life than isolated incidents.<br><br>
In a more contemporary setting, the destabilized Eastern European blood feuds have people eradicating one another with total religous and political justification, in their minds, on both sides. We see the artificially constrained semi-nomadic &quot;culturally mobile&quot; peoples of the Middle East taking a stroll now and then, too.<br><br>
I have a problem merging our activities of the Vietnam War with a cultural backdrop of &quot;locally acceptable slaughter&quot;. It is a burden beyond which I have the capacity to bear because our involvement was horrific enough to stand alone on its own merits.<br><br>
I do not agree with the continuing imperative for mass slaughter that moves around the globe. I think it is terrible. I cannot dismiss, however, the thought that in the minds of those going after each other, it is perfectly OK to them, and such is their point of view, and their right to it.<br><br>
Isn't this subject absolutely gruesome?<br><br>
I must be slipping into one of those black moods, again.<br><br>
Maybe I need to go out for a walk.                                                              
